   <abstract >This thesis investigates how critics respond to the fat body onstage, aiming to better understand how to develop positive fat representation. Through my research, I advocate for theatre to develop fat-positive practices. I argue that fat positivity in theatre must go beyond simply including fat bodies onstage. A fat-positive theatre would cast fat bodies in all roles, while maintaining the sensitivity that the fat body carries unique cultural assumptions and may require material changes to the theatrical processes. Adopting these fat-positive practices would involve a radical acceptance of fatness onstage. My research examines three notable plays as case studies to understand how the fat body is performed and received onstage in the United States. My first case study, 'night, Mother, takes place in the 1980s as a landmark example of how casting a fat body affected a production's reception. The other two case studies, Untitled Feminist Show and Fat Ham, focus on the 2010s and 2020s, to examine how recent shifts in fat activism and body-positive movements have impacted cultural understandings of the fat body. My research seeks to understand how these cultural shifts connect to critical receptions of the fat body onstage. Through these case studies, I aim to craft a narrative around the shifting ways we conceptualize the neutral body and how the fat body challenges this unspoken assumption. In this thesis, I use the term "neutral body" to refer to bodies that fit the cultural norms of an ideal performer and "non-neutral bodies" to identify fat bodies that visibly break the traditional mode of what we expect an actor to look like. This framework provides a way of thinking about how fat bodies are routinely excluded from representation and highlights the unspoken assumption that the fat body is not the ideal body.</abstract>
